    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cf-nse-08",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error is scoped out of this MRL 2 assessment because the ANSYS Fluent solver used in this study has been subjected to extensive vendor-managed verification campaigns covering the specific discretization schemes (second-order upwind, SIMPLE pressure-velocity coupling) applied in the pump model. The Software Quality Assurance factor (CF-SQA-01) provides independent confirmation that the solver implementation is correct through benchmark reproduction. At MRL 2, the ASME V&V 40 framework does not require a separate, stand-alone numerical solver error assessment when SQA evidence already documents solver correctness for the applicable equation set. Conducting a redundant solver-error assessment would not yield additional credibility evidence beyond what is already captured under SQA and Numerical Code Verification, and the marginal risk reduction does not justify the resource expenditure for a Class II device decision at this model risk level."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/morrison-cf-ue-09",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Use error is scoped out because the CFD analyses are executed exclusively by trained computational engineers operating under a documented simulation governance procedure (SGP-CFD-2023-04) that mandates peer review of all boundary-condition assignments, turbulence model selections, and post-processing scripts before results are accepted. The governance procedure includes a mandatory independent check of the hemolysis model coefficients against the published Giersiepen-Wurzinger constants, eliminating the primary pathway through which user-introduced parameter errors could propagate to the QoI. Under ASME V&V 40 at MRL 2, the combination of institutional governance controls and documented peer-review records constitutes sufficient mitigation of use-error risk, making a separate credibility-factor assessment for use error redundant with the process controls already in place. A dedicated use-error assessment at a higher gradation level would be warranted only if model influence were elevated to HIGH or if the device classification moved to Class III."
    },
